## Why This Is Asked
This question assesses your ability to design a memory-bounded streaming algorithm for heavy hitters with a fixed-coverage threshold.

## Key Concepts
- **Heavy Hitters:** Values that appear frequently in the stream
- **Streaming Algorithms:** Process data incrementally without storing the entire dataset
- **Bounded Memory:** Fixed-size data structures regardless of stream length
- **Threshold-Based Reporting:** Selecting the minimum subset that meets a coverage target

## Algorithm Analysis
- **Per-Element Update Cost:** O(log k) for heap maintenance (hash map lookup is O(1) average)
- **Per-Batch Query Cost:** O(k log k) to sort the heap and accumulate to the 95% threshold
- **Memory Usage:** O(M) for counts (if M is small) or O(unique values) with a hash map, plus O(k) for the heap

## Code Example
```javascript
class MinHeap {
  constructor(capacity) {
    this.heap = [];
    this.capacity = capacity;
  }
  push(item) {
    this.heap.push(item);
    this.bubbleUp(this.heap.length - 1);
    if (this.heap.length > this.capacity) this.pop();
  }
  pop() {
    const min = this.heap[0];
    const end = this.heap.pop();
    if (this.heap.length > 0) {
      this.heap[0] = end;
      this.bubbleDown(0);
    }
    return min;
  }
  bubbleUp(i) {
    while (i > 0) {
      const p = Math.floor((i - 1) / 2);
      if (this.heap[p].count <= this.heap[i].count) break;
      [this.heap[p], this.heap[i]] = [this.heap[i], this.heap[p]];
      i = p;
    }
  }
  bubbleDown(i) {
    while (true) {
      const l = 2 * i + 1, r = 2 * i + 2;
      let smallest = i;
      if (l < this.heap.length && this.heap[l].count < this.heap[smallest].count) smallest = l;
      if (r < this.heap.length && this.heap[r].count < this.heap[smallest].count) smallest = r;
      if (smallest === i) break;
      [this.heap[i], this.heap[smallest]] = [this.heap[smallest], this.heap[i]];
      i = smallest;
    }
  }
}

const counts = new Map();
let total = 0;
const k = 20;
const heap = new MinHeap(k);

function updateBatch(batch) {
  for (const v of batch) {
    const count = (counts.get(v) || 0) + 1;
    counts.set(v, count);
    total++;
    heap.push({ value: v, count });
  }
}

function get95Cover() {
  const sorted = [...heap.heap].sort((a, b) => b.count - a.count);
  const threshold = total * 0.95;
  let sum = 0;
  const result = [];
  for (const item of sorted) {
    sum += item.count;
    result.push(item.value);
    if (sum >= threshold) break;
  }
  if (sum < threshold) {
    return [...counts.keys()];
  }
  return result;
}
```

## Trade-offs
The heap-only approach tracks only the top-k values, so if fewer than k values dominate the stream, we may not reach 95% coverage. In such cases, the algorithm falls back to returning all seen values. For guaranteed bounded memory with approximate coverage, consider probabilistic methods like Count-Min Sketch or Lossy Counting.

