## Why This Is Asked
This question tests your ability to design a fixed-memory streaming algorithm for heavy hitter detection—a common requirement in real-world scenarios like analytics dashboards, network monitoring, and recommendation systems.

## Key Concepts
- **Misra-Gries algorithm**: A space-efficient algorithm for finding items that appear more than 1/m of the time
- **Heavy hitters**: Values that appear frequently in a stream (above a threshold)
- **Space-time tradeoffs**: Analyzing memory usage versus per-element update time

## Algorithm Analysis
| Metric | Complexity |
|--------|------------|
| Per-element update | O(1) |
| Per-batch query | O(m) = O(1) since m=2 |
| Memory usage | O(m) = O(2) = O(1) fixed |

## Code Example
```javascript
class MisraGries {
  constructor(m = 2) {
    this.m = m;
    this.counters = new Map();
  }

  add(x) {
    if (this.counters.has(x)) {
      this.counters.set(x, this.counters.get(x) + 1);
    } else if (this.counters.size < this.m) {
      this.counters.set(x, 1);
    } else {
      for (const [key, val] of this.counters) {
        this.counters.set(key, val - 1);
        if (this.counters.get(key) === 0) this.counters.delete(key);
      }
    }
  }

  getHeavyHitters() {
    return Array.from(this.counters.entries())
      .filter(([_, count]) => count > 0)
      .map(([value, count]) => ({ value, count }));
  }
}
```

## Small Example (m=2, stream: 1, 2, 1, 3, 1, 2)
| Element | Counter State | Heavy Hitters |
|---------|---------------|---------------|
| 1 | {1:1} | 1 |
| 2 | {1:1, 2:1} | 1, 2 |
| 1 | {1:2, 2:1} | 1, 2 |
| 3 | {1:1, 2:0} → {1:1} | 1 |
| 1 | {1:2} | 1 |
| 2 | {1:2, 2:1} | 1, 2 |

## Follow-up Questions
- **Sliding windows**: Use a timestamped variant or combine with a separate structure tracking element ages
- **Ties**: Resolve by recency (most recently incremented) or arbitrarily since counts are equal
- **Accuracy**: Misra-Gries guarantees all heavy hitters are found but may include false positives; lowering the threshold (increasing m) reduces false positives at higher memory cost

## Why This Is Asked

This problem tests real-time data tracking with batched updates and sliding window counts. It evaluates the ability to design a data structure that combines efficient timestamp-based aggregation with per-session lookup while managing amortized cleanup.

## Key Concepts

- Batched online updates with timestamp ordering
- Sliding window counts with expiration
- Two-tier data structures (ordered map + hash map)
- Amortized analysis versus naive recalculation

## Code Example

```javascript
class SessionTracker {
  constructor(W) {
    this.W = W;
    this.idToTime = new Map();
    this.timeToCount = new Map();
  }

  processBatch(events, currentTime) {
    for (const { sessionId, time, isNew } of events) {
      if (isNew) {
        this.idToTime.set(sessionId, time);
        this.timeToCount.set(time, (this.timeToCount.get(time) || 0) + 1);
      } else {
        const oldTime = this.idToTime.get(sessionId);
        this.timeToCount.set(oldTime, this.timeToCount.get(oldTime) - 1);
        this.idToTime.set(sessionId, time);
        this.timeToCount.set(time, (this.timeToCount.get(time) || 0) + 1);
      }
    }
    this.expireOldSessions(currentTime);
  }

  expireOldSessions(currentTime) {
    const threshold = currentTime - this.W;
    for (const [time, count] of this.timeToCount) {
      if (time < threshold) {
        this.timeToCount.delete(time);
      }
    }
  }

  countActive(currentTime) {
    const threshold = currentTime - this.W;
    let count = 0;
    for (const [time, c] of this.timeToCount) {
      if (time >= threshold) count += c;
    }
    return count;
  }
}
```

## Analysis

**Preprocessing**: O(1) — just initialize empty maps.

**Memory**: O(S) where S is the number of unique timestamps with active sessions; worst case O(N) for N sessions if all have distinct timestamps.

**Update**: Each event is O(log T) for the ordered map insertion/deletion, where T is the number of unique timestamps. With B events per batch, this is O(B log T) amortized.

**Query**: O(T) in the worst case — must scan all timestamps in the window. Using an ordered map with prefix sum augmentation could reduce this to O(log T).

**Comparison to naive recalculation**: Recalculating from scratch after each batch would require O(N) per query, where N is total active sessions. The two-tier structure provides O(1) lookup per session update and O(T) or O(log T) queries — a significant improvement when batches are processed frequently and queries are intermittent.

## Why This Is Asked
This question tests the ability to design incremental data structures that handle batch updates with strong worst-case guarantees, and to reason about amortized costs versus rebuilding from scratch.

## Key Concepts
- DSU with parity (union-find with bipartite tracking)
- Incremental graph property maintenance
- Amortized analysis (inverse Ackermann function)
- Batch processing optimization

## Code Example
```javascript
class ParityDSU {
  constructor(n) {
    this.parent = Array.from({ length: n }, (_, i) => i);
    this.parity = new Array(n).fill(0);
    this.rank = new Array(n).fill(0);
    this.isBipartite = true;
  }

  find(x) {
    if (this.parent[x] !== x) {
      const root = this.find(this.parent[x]);
      this.parity[x] ^= this.parity[this.parent[x]];
      this.parent[x] = root;
    }
    return this.parent[x];
  }

  union(x, y) {
    const rootX = this.find(x);
    const rootY = this.find(y);
    if (rootX === rootY) {
      if (this.parity[x] === this.parity[y]) {
        this.isBipartite = false;
      }
      return;
    }
    if (this.rank[rootX] < this.rank[rootY]) {
      this.parent[rootX] = rootY;
      this.parity[rootX] = this.parity[x] ^ this.parity[y] ^ 1;
    } else if (this.rank[rootX] > this.rank[rootY]) {
      this.parent[rootY] = rootX;
      this.parity[rootY] = this.parity[x] ^ this.parity[y] ^ 1;
    } else {
      this.parent[rootY] = rootX;
      this.rank[rootX]++;
      this.parity[rootY] = this.parity[x] ^ this.parity[y] ^ 1;
    }
  }

  processBatch(edges) {
    for (const [u, v] of edges) {
      this.union(u, v);
    }
    return this.isBipartite;
  }
}
```

## Comparison to Recomputing from Scratch
- **DSU with parity**: O(B α(n)) per batch, O(1) query
- **BFS/DFS recomputation**: O(n + m) per batch

The DSU approach provides a significant speedup when B << m, as it reuses information from previous batches rather than recomputing the entire graph structure.

