## Why This Is Asked
This question evaluates your ability to design efficient dynamic ranking systems with batched updates, requiring you to balance update locality against query efficiency in real-world scenarios.

## Key Concepts
- Ordered maps for score-based organization
- Lazy maximum score tracking to avoid unnecessary recomputation
- Efficient top-K extraction through bucket traversal
- Amortized time complexity analysis
- Memory usage optimization techniques

## Code Example
```javascript
// Pseudocode implementation
class TopKKeeper {
  constructor(users) {
    this.scoreToIds = new TreeMap(); // score -> TreeSet of user IDs
    this.userToScore = new HashMap(); // user ID -> current score
    this.maxScore = null;

    // Initialize in O(n)
    for (const [id, score] of users) {
      this.addUserToBucket(id, score);
    }
  }

  updateBatch(updates) {
    // Process B updates in O(B log n)
    for (const [id, delta] of updates) {
      const oldScore = this.userToScore.get(id);
      const newScore = oldScore + delta;

      this.removeUserFromBucket(id, oldScore);
      this.addUserToBucket(id, newScore);
    }
  }

  getTopK(k) {
    // Extract top-K in O(K log n)
    const result = [];
    let currentScore = this.maxScore;
    let remaining = k;

    while (remaining > 0 && currentScore !== null) {
      const ids = this.scoreToIds.get(currentScore);
      const takeCount = Math.min(remaining, ids.size());

      // Extract first 'takeCount' IDs (already sorted)
      result.push(...Array.from(ids).slice(0, takeCount));
      remaining -= takeCount;
      currentScore = this.scoreToIds.lowerKey(currentScore);
    }

    return result.slice(0, k);
  }
}
```

## Optimizations
1. **Lazy Maximum Updates**: Only recompute the maximum score when the current maximum bucket becomes empty, avoiding O(log n) overhead on every update.

2. **Batch Top-K Extraction**: Cache the current top-K result and only recompute when updates affect users in the top-K, reducing query frequency from every batch to only when necessary.

## Comparison to Rebuilding
Rebuilding from scratch would require O(n) time per batch to sort all users, resulting in O(n × batches) total time. Our approach achieves O(B log n) updates and O(K log n) queries, providing significant improvement when K << n and B is moderate.

## Complexity Analysis
- **Initialization**: O(n) - one insertion per user
- **Batch Updates**: O(B log n) - each update requires remove/insert operations
- **Top-K Query**: O(K log n) - traverse at most K score buckets
- **Space**: O(n) - store user-score mappings and score buckets

## Why This Question Is Asked
This question evaluates understanding of online quantile estimation using the P² algorithm, a space-efficient alternative to GK-style sketches. It tests practical knowledge of update mechanics, error behavior, and the trade-offs between approximation and exact computation in streaming contexts.

## Key Concepts
- The P² algorithm uses five fixed-position marker heights to approximate quantiles
- Piecewise-linear interpolation between markers yields quantile estimates
- Per-element updates are constant time with fixed memory overhead
- The algorithm provides guarantees that improve with larger sample sizes

## Code Example
```javascript
class P2Quantile {
  constructor(quantile = 0.5) {
    this.quantile = quantile;
    this.n = 0;
    this.markers = [0, 0, 0, 0, 0];
    this.positions = [0, 0.25, 0.5, 0.75, 1].map(p => p * 2);
  }

  update(value) {
    this.n++;
    if (this.n < 5) {
      this.markers[this.n - 1] = value;
      this.markers.sort((a, b) => a - b);
      return;
    }

    let j = this.quantile < 0.5 ? 1 : 3;
    if (value >= this.markers[j]) j++;

    for (let i = j; i < 5; i++) this.positions[i]++;

    for (let i = 1; i < 4; i++) {
      const d = this.positions[i] - this.positions[i-1];
      const target = (i + 1) * this.n / 4;
      if ((d > 1 && this.positions[i] < target) || 
          (d < 1 && this.positions[i] > target)) {
        const sign = d > 1 ? 1 : -1;
        this.markers[i] += sign * Math.min(d, Math.abs(this.positions[i] - target));
        this.positions[i] += sign;
      }
    }
  }

  getQuantile() {
    return this.markers[2];
  }
}
```

## Error Analysis
The P² algorithm exhibits decreasing error as more elements are processed. For uniform distributions, error is minimal; for skewed distributions, error may be slightly higher but remains bounded. Larger batch sizes reduce the frequency of updates but do not fundamentally alter the error characteristics.

## Comparison to Sorted Buffer
Maintaining a full sorted buffer of size N provides exact median computation but requires O(N) memory and O(log N) insertion time per element. The P² algorithm trades this exactness for constant memory and constant update time, making it suitable for memory-constrained streaming applications where approximate quantiles suffice.

